[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] Several different queue data structures can be used.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] This FIFO-queue-based implementation yields a breadth-first search.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] A stack (LIFO queue) will yield a depth-first algorithm.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] A best-first branch-and-bound algorithm can be obtained by using a priority queue that sorts nodes on their lower bounds.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] Examples of best-first search algorithms with this premise are Dijkstra's algorithm and its descendant A* search.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-bound] The depth-first variant is recommended when no good heuristic is available for producing an initial solution, because it quickly produces full solutions, and therefore upper bounds.
