[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-cut] There are also a large number of variations of these branching strategies, such as using strong branching early on when pseudo cost branching is relatively uninformative and then switching to pseudo cost branching later when there is enough branching history for pseudo cost to be informative.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] In applied mathematics, **branch and price** is a method of combinatorial optimization for solving integer linear programming (ILP) and mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems with many variables.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] The method is a hybrid of branch and bound and column generation methods.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Branch and price is a branch and bound method in which at each node of the search tree, columns may be added to the linear programming relaxation (LP relaxation).
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] At the start of the algorithm, sets of columns are excluded from the LP relaxation in order to reduce the computational and memory requirements and then columns are added back to the LP relaxation as needed.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] The approach is based on the observation that for large problems most columns will be nonbasic and have their corresponding variable equal to zero in any optimal solution.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Thus, the large majority of the columns are irrelevant for solving the problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] The algorithm typically begins by using a reformulation, such as Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition, to form what is known as the **Master Problem**.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] The decomposition is performed to obtain a problem formulation that gives better bounds when the relaxation is solved than when the relaxation of the original formulation is solved.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] But, the decomposition usually contains many variables and so a modified version, called the **Restricted Master Problem**, that only considers a subset of the columns is solved.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Then, to check for optimality, a subproblem called the **pricing problem** is solved to find columns that can enter the basis and reduce the objective function (for a minimization problem).
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] This involves finding a column that has a negative reduced cost.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Note that the pricing problem itself may be difficult to solve but since it is not necessary to find the column with the most negative reduced cost, heuristic and local search methods can be used.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] The subproblem must only be solved to completion in order to prove that an optimal solution to the Restricted Master Problem is also an optimal solution to the Master Problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Each time a column is found with negative reduced cost, it is added to the Restricted Master Problem and the relaxation is reoptimized.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] If no columns can enter the basis and the solution to the relaxation is not integer, then branching occurs.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] Most branch and price algorithms are problem specific since the problem must be formulated in such a way so that effective branching rules can be formulated and so that the pricing problem is relatively easy to solve.
[src:exact-algorithms/branch-and-price] If cutting planes are used to tighten LP relaxations within a branch and price algorithm, the method is known as **branch price and cut**.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization is related to operations research, algorithm theory, and computational complexity theory.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] It has important applications in several fields, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, auction theory, software engineering, VLSI, applied mathematics and theoretical computer science.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] There is a large amount of literature on polynomial-time algorithms for certain special classes of discrete optimization.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] A considerable amount of it is unified by the theory of linear programming.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Some examples of combinatorial optimization problems that are covered by this framework are shortest paths and shortest-path trees, flows and circulations, spanning trees, matching, and matroid problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Combinatorial optimization problems can be viewed as searching for the best element of some set of discrete items; therefore, in principle, any sort of search algorithm or metaheuristic can be used to solve them.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] However, generic search algorithms are not guaranteed to find an optimal solution first, nor are they guaranteed to run quickly (in polynomial time).
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Since some discrete optimization problems are NP-complete, such as the traveling salesman (decision) problem, this is expected unless P=NP.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] For each combinatorial optimization problem, there is a corresponding decision problem that asks whether there is a feasible solution for some particular measure $m_{0}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] For example, if there is a graph G which contains vertices u and v , an optimization problem might be "find a path from u to v that uses the fewest edges".
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] This problem might have an answer of, say, 4.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] A corresponding decision problem would be "is there a path from u to v that uses 10 or fewer edges?" This problem can be answered with a simple 'yes' or 'no'.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] The field of approximation algorithms deals with algorithms to find near-optimal solutions to hard problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] The usual decision version is then an inadequate definition of the problem since it only specifies acceptable solutions.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Even though we could introduce suitable decision problems, the problem is then more naturally characterized as an optimization problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] An *NP-optimization problem* (NPO) is a combinatorial optimization problem with the following additional conditions.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Note that the below referred polynomials are functions of the size of the respective functions' inputs, not the size of some implicit set of input instances.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] This implies that the corresponding decision problem is in NP.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] In computer science, interesting optimization problems usually have the above properties and are therefore NPO problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] A problem is additionally called a P-optimization (PO) problem, if there exists an algorithm which finds optimal solutions in polynomial time.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Often, when dealing with the class NPO, one is interested in optimization problems for which the decision versions are NP-complete.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Note that hardness relations are always with respect to some reduction.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] Due to the connection between approximation algorithms and computational optimization problems, reductions which preserve approximation in some respect are for this subject preferred than the usual Turing and Karp reductions.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] An example of such a reduction would be L-reduction.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] For this reason, optimization problems with NP-complete decision versions are not necessarily called NPO-complete.
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] An NPO problem is called *polynomially bounded* (PB) if, for every instance x and for every solution $y\in f(x)$ , the measure $m(x,y)$ is bounded by a polynomial function of the size of x .
[src:exact-algorithms/combinatorial-optimization] The class NPOPB is the class of NPO problems that are polynomially-bounded.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] In mathematical optimization, the **cutting-plane method** is any of a variety of optimization methods that iteratively refine a feasible set or objective function by means of linear inequalities, termed *cuts*.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Such procedures are commonly used to find integer solutions to mixed integer linear programming (MILP) problems, as well as to solve general, not necessarily differentiable convex optimization problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The use of cutting planes to solve MILP was introduced by Ralph E.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods for MILP work by solving a non-integer linear program, the linear relaxation of the given integer program.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The theory of Linear Programming dictates that under mild assumptions (if the linear program has an optimal solution, and if the feasible region does not contain a line), one can always find an extreme point or a corner point that is optimal.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The obtained optimum is tested for being an integer solution.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] If it is not, there is guaranteed to exist a linear inequality that *separates* the optimum from the convex hull of the true feasible set.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Finding such an inequality is the *separation problem*, and such an inequality is a *cut*.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] A cut can be added to the relaxed linear program.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Then, the current non-integer solution is no longer feasible to the relaxation.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] This process is repeated until an optimal integer solution is found.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Cutting-plane methods for general convex continuous optimization and variants are known under various names: Kelley's method, Kelley–Cheney–Goldstein method, and bundle methods.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] They are popularly used for non-differentiable convex minimization, where a convex objective function and its subgradient can be evaluated efficiently but usual gradient methods for differentiable optimization can not be used.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] This situation is most typical for the concave maximization of Lagrangian dual functions.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Another common situation is the application of the Dantzig–Wolfe decomposition to a structured optimization problem in which formulations with an exponential number of variables are obtained.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Generating these variables on demand by means of delayed column generation is identical to performing a cutting plane on the respective dual problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Cutting planes were proposed by Ralph Gomory in the 1950s as a method for solving integer programming and mixed-integer programming problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] However, most experts, including Gomory himself, considered them to be impractical due to numerical instability, as well as ineffective because many rounds of cuts were needed to make progress towards the solution.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Things turned around when in the mid-1990s Gérard Cornuéjols and co-workers showed them to be very effective in combination with branch-and-bound (called branch-and-cut) and ways to overcome numerical instabilities.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Nowadays, all commercial MILP solvers use Gomory cuts in one way or another.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Gomory cuts are very efficiently generated from a simplex tableau, whereas many other types of cuts are either expensive or even NP-hard to separate.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Among other general cuts for MILP, most notably lift-and-project dominates Gomory cuts.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] where A is a matrix and b , c is a vector.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The vector x is unknown and is to be found in order to maximize the objective while respecting the linear constraints.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The method proceeds by first dropping the requirement that the xi be integers and solving the associated relaxed linear programming problem to obtain a basic feasible solution.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Geometrically, this solution will be a vertex of the convex polytope consisting of all feasible points.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] If this vertex is not an integer point then the method finds a hyperplane with the vertex on one side and all feasible integer points on the other.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] This is then added as an additional linear constraint to exclude the vertex found, creating a modified linear program.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The new program is then solved and the process is repeated until an integer solution is found.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] where *xi* is a basic variable and the *xj'*s are the nonbasic variables (i.e. the basic solution which is an optimal solution to the relaxed linear program is $x_{i}={\bar {b}}_{i}$ and $x_{j}=0$ ).
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] We write coefficients ${\bar {b}}_{i}$ and ${\bar {a}}_{i,j}$ with a bar to denote the last tableau produced by the simplex method.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] These coefficients are different from the coefficients in the matrix A and the vector b.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Consider now a basic variable $x_{i}$ which is not an integer.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] For any integer point in the feasible region, the left side is an integer since all the terms $x_{i}$ , $x_{j}$ , $\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor$ , $\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ are integers.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The right side of this equation is strictly less than 1: indeed, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor$ is strictly less than 1 while $-\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Therefore the common value must be less than or equal to 0.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] must hold for any integer point in the feasible region.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] So the inequality above excludes the basic feasible solution and thus is a cut with the desired properties.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] More precisely, ${\bar {b}}_{i}-\lfloor {\bar {b}}_{i}\rfloor -\sum _{j}({\bar {a}}_{i,j}-\lfloor {\bar {a}}_{i,j}\rfloor )x_{j}$ is negative for any integer point in the feasible region, and strictly positive for the basic feasible (non integer) solution of the relaxed linear program.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] Cutting plane methods are also applicable in nonlinear programming.
[src:exact-algorithms/cutting-plane-method] The underlying principle is to approximate the feasible region of a nonlinear (convex) program by a finite set of closed half spaces and to solve a sequence of approximating linear programs.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] An **integer programming**, also known as **integer optimization**, problem is a mathematical optimization or feasibility program in which some or all of the variables are restricted to be integers.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In many settings the term refers to **integer linear programming** (ILP), in which the objective function and the constraints (other than the integer constraints) are linear.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Integer programming is NP-complete (the difficult part is showing the NP membership).
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In particular, the special case of 0–1 integer linear programming, in which unknowns are binary, and only the restrictions must be satisfied, is one of Karp's 21 NP-complete problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] If some decision variables are not discrete, the problem is known as a **mixed-integer programming** problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Integer linear programs can be expressed either in *canonical form* or *standard form* (both as defined below), which are different from each other.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] where $\mathbf {c} \in \mathbb {R} ^{n},\mathbf {b} \in \mathbb {R} ^{m}$ are vectors and $A\in \mathbb {R} ^{m\times n}$ is a matrix.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] As with linear programs, ILPs not in standard form can be converted to standard form by eliminating inequalities, introducing slack variables ( $\mathbf {s}$ ) and replacing variables that are not sign-constrained with the difference of two sign-constrained variables.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The plot on the right shows the following problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The feasible integer points are shown in red, and the red dashed lines indicate their convex hull, which is the smallest convex polyhedron that contains all of these points.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The blue lines together with the coordinate axes define the polyhedron of the LP relaxation, which is given by the inequalities without the integrality constraint.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The goal of the optimization is to move the black dashed line as far upward while still touching the polyhedron.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The optimal solutions of the integer problem are the points $(1,2)$ and $(2,2)$ that both have an objective value of 2.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The unique optimum of the relaxation is $(1.8,2.8)$ with objective value of 2.8.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] If the solution of the relaxation is rounded to the nearest integers, it is not feasible for the ILP.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The following is a reduction from minimum vertex cover to integer programming that will serve as the proof of NP-hardness.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Any feasible solution to the integer program will be nonzero on a subset of vertices.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The first constraint implies that at least one end point of every edge is included in this subset.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Therefore, the solution describes a vertex cover.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Additionally given some vertex cover C, $y_{v}$ can be set to 1 for any $v\in C$ and to 0 for any $v\not \in C$ thus giving us a feasible solution to the integer program.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Thus we can conclude that if we minimize the sum of $y_{v}$ we have also found the minimum vertex cover.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Other integer variables represent decisions (e.g. whether to include an edge in a graph) and so should only take on the value 0 or 1.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] These considerations occur frequently in practice and so integer linear programming can be used in many applications areas, some of which are briefly described below.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Mixed-integer programming has many applications in industrial productions, including job-shop modelling.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] One important example happens in agricultural production planning and involves determining production yield for several crops that can share resources (e.g. land, labor, capital, seeds, fertilizer, etc.).
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] A possible objective is to maximize the total production, without exceeding the available resources.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In some cases, this can be expressed in terms of a linear program, but the variables must be constrained to be integer.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] These problems involve service and vehicle scheduling in transportation networks.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] For example, a problem may involve assigning buses or subways to individual routes so that a timetable can be met, and also to equip them with drivers.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Here binary decision variables indicate whether a bus or subway is assigned to a route and whether a driver is assigned to a particular train or subway.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The zero–one programming technique has been successfully applied to solve a project selection problem in which projects are mutually exclusive and/or technologically interdependent.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Territorial partitioning or districting problems consist of partitioning a geographical region into districts in order to plan some operations while considering different criteria or constraints.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Some requirements for this problem are: contiguity, compactness, balance or equity, respect of natural boundaries, and socio-economic homogeneity.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Some applications for this type of problem include: political districting, school districting, health services districting and waste management districting.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The goal of these problems is to design a network of lines to install so that a predefined set of communication requirements are met and the total cost of the network is minimal.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] This requires optimizing both the topology of the network along with setting the capacities of the various lines.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In many cases, the capacities are constrained to be integer quantities.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Usually there are, depending on the technology used, additional restrictions that can be modeled as linear inequalities with integer or binary variables.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The task of frequency planning in GSM mobile networks involves distributing available frequencies across the antennas so that users can be served and interference is minimized between the antennas.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] This problem can be formulated as an integer linear program in which binary variables indicate whether a frequency is assigned to an antenna.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The naive way to solve an ILP is to simply remove the constraint that **x** is integer, solve the corresponding LP (called the LP relaxation of the ILP), and then round the entries of the solution to the LP relaxation.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] But, not only may this solution not be optimal, it may not even be feasible; that is, it may violate some constraint.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Consequently, the solution returned by the simplex algorithm is guaranteed to be integral.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] To show that every basic feasible solution is integral, let $\mathbf {x}$ be an arbitrary basic feasible solution .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Since $\mathbf {x}$ is feasible, we know that $A\mathbf {x} =\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Let $\mathbf {x} _{0}=[x_{n_{1}},x_{n_{2}},\cdots ,x_{n_{j}}]$ be the elements corresponding to the basis columns for the basic solution $\mathbf {x}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] By definition of a basis, there is some square submatrix B of A with linearly independent columns such that $B\mathbf {x} _{0}=\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Since the columns of B are linearly independent and B is square, B is nonsingular, and therefore by assumption, B is unimodular and so $\det(B)=\pm 1$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Also, since B is nonsingular, it is invertible and therefore $\mathbf {x} _{0}=B^{-1}\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Here $B^{\mathrm {adj} }$ denotes the adjugate of B and is integral because B is integral.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] When the matrix A is not totally unimodular, there are a variety of algorithms that can be used to solve integer linear programs exactly.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] One class of algorithms are cutting plane methods, which work by solving the LP relaxation and then adding linear constraints that drive the solution towards being integer without excluding any integer feasible points.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Another class of algorithms are variants of the branch and bound method.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] For example, the branch and cut method that combines both branch and bound and cutting plane methods.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Branch and bound algorithms have a number of advantages over algorithms that only use cutting planes.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] One advantage is that the algorithms can be terminated early and as long as at least one integral solution has been found, a feasible, although not necessarily optimal, solution can be returned.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Further, the solutions of the LP relaxations can be used to provide a worst-case estimate of how far from optimality the returned solution is.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Finally, branch and bound methods can be used to return multiple optimal solutions.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Suppose A is an *m*-by-*n* integer matrix and $\mathbf {b}$ is an *m*-by-1 integer vector.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] We focus on the feasibility problem, which is to decide whether there exists an *n*-by-1 vector $\mathbf {x}$ satisfying $A\mathbf {x} \leq \mathbf {b}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Let *V* be the maximum absolute value of the coefficients in A and $\mathbf {b}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] If *n* (the number of variables) is a fixed constant, then the feasibility problem can be solved in time polynomial in *m* and log *V*.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The case *n*=2 was solved in 1981 by Herbert Scarf.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The general case was solved in 1983 by Hendrik Lenstra, combining ideas by László Lovász and Peter van Emde Boas.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In the special case of 0-1 ILP, Lenstra's algorithm is equivalent to complete enumeration: the number of all possible solutions is fixed (2*n*), and checking the feasibility of each solution can be done in time poly(*m*, log *V*).
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In the general case, where each variable can be an arbitrary integer, complete enumeration is impossible.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Here, Lenstra's algorithm uses ideas from Geometry of numbers.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] It transforms the original problem into an equivalent one with the following property: either the existence of a solution $\mathbf {x}$ is obvious, or the value of $x_{n}$ (the *n*-th variable) belongs to an interval whose length is bounded by a function of *n*.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In the latter case, the problem is reduced to a bounded number of lower-dimensional problems.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] These algorithms can also be used for **mixed integer linear programs** (MILP) - programs in which some variables are integer and some variables are real.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The original algorithm of Lenstra has run-time $2^{O(n^{3})}\cdot poly(d,L)$ , where n is the number of integer variables, d is the number of continuous variables, and *L* is the binary encoding size of the problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Using techniques from later algorithms, the factor $2^{O(n^{3})}$ can be improved to $2^{O(n\log n)}$ or to $n^{n}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Since integer linear programming is NP-hard, many problem instances are intractable and so heuristic methods must be used instead.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] For example, tabu search can be used to search for solutions to ILPs.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] To use tabu search to solve ILPs, moves can be defined as incrementing or decrementing an integer constrained variable of a feasible solution while keeping all other integer-constrained variables constant.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The unrestricted variables are then solved for.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Short-term memory can consist of previously tried solutions while medium-term memory can consist of values for the integer constrained variables that have resulted in high objective values (assuming the ILP is a maximization problem).
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Finally, long-term memory can guide the search towards integer values that have not previously been tried.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] There are also a variety of other problem-specific heuristics, such as the k-opt heuristic for the traveling salesman problem.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] A disadvantage of heuristic methods is that if they fail to find a solution, it cannot be determined whether it is because there is no feasible solution or whether the algorithm simply was unable to find one.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Further, it is usually impossible to quantify how close to optimal a solution returned by these methods are.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] It is often the case that the matrix A that defines the integer program is *sparse*.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In particular, this occurs when the matrix has a block structure, which is the case in many applications.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The sparsity of the matrix can be measured as follows.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The *graph* of A has vertices corresponding to columns of A , and two columns form an edge if A has a row where both columns have nonzero entries.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Equivalently, the vertices correspond to variables, and two variables form an edge if they share an inequality.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] The *sparsity measure* d of A is the minimum of the tree-depth of the graph of A and the tree-depth of the graph of the transpose of A .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Let a be the *numeric measure* of A defined as the maximum absolute value of any entry of A .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Let n be the number of variables of the integer program.
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Then it was shown in 2018 that integer programming can be solved in strongly polynomial and fixed-parameter tractable time parameterized by a and d .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] That is, for some computable function f and some constant k , integer programming can be solved in time $f(a,d)n^{k}$ .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] In particular, the time is independent of the right-hand side b and objective function c .
[src:exact-algorithms/integer-programming] Moreover, in contrast to the classical result of Lenstra, where the number n of variables is a parameter, here the number n of variables is a variable part of the input.
